{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:53:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:53:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.13,0.18,0.31,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59025"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7066"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44436"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"2335"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4370"},{"type":"tags","id":"4371"},{"type":"tags","id":"12033"},{"type":"tags","id":"12034"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59025"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea and vomiting. She is 24 weeks pregnant with her first child. She has a history of type 1 diabetes mellitus diagnosed at age 12 and hyperlipidaemia. Her regular medications include insulin lispro and insulin glargine. She reports difficulty managing her blood glucose levels over the past week due to her nausea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender, with a palpable gravid uterus consistent with dates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose: 12.0 mmol/L (4.0-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine ketones: 3+\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum bicarbonate: 14 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 14.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 45 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 50 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn obstetric ultrasound shows a single live fetus with normal anatomy and growth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant fetal risk associated with this patient\u0027s current emergency department presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congenital malformations","Intrauterine growth restriction","Preterm labour","Perinatal mortality","Fetal macrosomia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)\u003C/strong\u003E in pregnancy, which carries significant risks for both the mother and the fetus. Of the options provided, \u003Cstrong\u003Eperinatal mortality\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant and immediate risk to the fetus in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital malformations\u003C/strong\u003E are indeed a risk associated with poorly controlled diabetes in pregnancy, particularly during the first trimester when organogenesis occurs. However, at 24 weeks gestation, major congenital malformations have already occurred or been avoided, making this less relevant to the acute situation described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrauterine growth restriction\u003C/strong\u003E can be a consequence of chronic poor glycemic control in diabetic pregnancies, but it is not the most immediate or severe risk in the context of acute DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreterm labour\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential complication of DKA in pregnancy, but it is not as directly life-threatening to the fetus as the risk of perinatal mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFetal macrosomia\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with chronic hyperglycemia throughout pregnancy, particularly in the third trimester. It is not an acute risk in the setting of DKA and is less severe than the risk of perinatal mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDKA in pregnancy is associated with a significantly increased risk of perinatal mortality, with rates reported to be as high as 9-35%. The fetal death can occur due to several factors, including maternal acidosis, electrolyte imbalances, and hypoxia. Rapid maternal ketone body production can lead to fetal acidosis, as ketones readily cross the placenta. Additionally, maternal dehydration and hypotension can compromise uteroplacental blood flow, further jeopardizing fetal well-being.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrompt recognition and treatment of DKA in pregnancy is crucial to mitigate these risks. Management typically involves aggressive fluid resuscitation, insulin therapy, electrolyte correction, and close monitoring of both maternal and fetal status. Fetal monitoring is essential during treatment, as rapid changes in maternal glucose levels and fluid status can cause fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) can occur in pregnancy and requires prompt recognition and treatment.","Pregnancy is a diabetogenic state, and women with pre-existing diabetes are at increased risk of DKA.","Nausea and vomiting in a pregnant woman with diabetes should raise suspicion for DKA, even if blood glucose levels are not markedly elevated.","DKA in pregnancy is associated with significant fetal risks, including increased perinatal mortality."],"references":["Diguisto C, Strachan MWJ, Churchill D, Ayman G, Knight M. A study of diabetic ketoacidosis in the pregnant population in the United Kingdom: investigating the incidence, aetiology, management and outcomes. Diabet Med. 2022 Apr;39(4)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44436"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44436"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T13:48:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T14:21:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7066"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},